      {
        "id": "docling_scihub_s11661-013-1726-7.pdf_2_0",
        "observed_type": "caption",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Fig. 2-Microstructures of alloy B in (a) as-cast and (b) SHTed (8 h) conditions; and EBSD results of (c) a-Fe in (b) and (d) STed -Fe in (b).",
        "bbox": [
          0.04651164179586509,
          0.44186046518228644,
          0.8798449751291985,
          0.45348837202701586
        ],
        "order": 39
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_scihub_s11661-013-1726-7.pdf_2_38",
        "observed_type": "caption",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Table II. Chemical Compositions of Iron-Rich Intermetallics in the As-Cast and SHTed Conditions",
        "bbox": [
          0.1472868452620134,
          0.47383720929565853,
          0.792635651491862,
          0.48546511614038795
        ],
        "order": 40
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_scihub_s11661-013-1726-7.pdf_2_41",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "SHT for 8 hours. As shown in Figure 2(c), however, the EBSD results with a mean angular deviation (MAD) of 0.452, lower than 0.7 which is considered to be critical for an accurate solution, indicate that this phase is still the a-Fe (body-centered cubic with a, b, and c as 1.265 nm''1). Moreover, the platelet-like intermetallic phase formed during the SHT has a similar chemical composition to the B-Fe obtained in the as-cast condition (Table II) and thus is termed as solid-state-transformed B-Fe (STed -Fe) to distinguish it from the -Fe directly precipitated from liquid metal during solidification. The formation of the STed -Fe is further confirmed a low MAD value of 0.258 as measured by EBSD (Figure 2(d)), The STed -Fe is most likely to have the same crystal structure as the solidified B-Fe (tetragonal with a and b of 0.634 mm and c of 1.488 nmIl) due to their similar diffraction patterns. However, the STed p-Fe has lower Cu content than the B-Fe (Table II), and the replacement of the Cu by Al",
        "bbox": [
          0.4864341087849712,
          0.6293604653626401,
          0.8953488366810338,
          0.8924418604182782
        ],
        "order": 42
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_scihub_s11661-013-1726-7.pdf_2_39",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "contents of Mn and Si, which is consistent with the literature. 16,30 After being SHTed for 8 hours, almost the entire amount of AlCu is dissolved into the Al matrix as shown in Figure 2(b). It is also interesting to note that the Chinese script a-Fe phase becomes unstable and is transformed into a small amount of short intermetallic platelets, leading to the fragmentation of the x-Fe.",
        "bbox": [
          0.04457364510914881,
          0.6307043651387052,
          0.45155038319834484,
          0.7399318711276386
        ],
        "order": 43
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_scihub_s11661-013-1726-7.pdf_2_40",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The chemical compositions of the iron-rich intermetallics in Alloy B in the as-cast and SHTed (for 8 hours) conditions measured by SEM-EDS are shown in Table Il. It can be found that higher Al contents are detected in the a-Fe and STed B-Fe after SHT than the corresponding iron-rich phases solidified directly from the liquid. This can be attributed to the partial contribution of the surrounding Al matrix due to the small sizes of the fragmented a-Fe and STed B-Fe particles after SHT. Compared with the as-cast condition, it can be found that the iron content in a-Fe is reduced after",
        "bbox": [
          0.04457364510914881,
          0.7412790697849997,
          0.4515503768546758,
          0.8909883714459522
        ],
        "order": 44
      }
    ]
